1. Introduction
Dear User, 
Welcome to the BGIs project. The basis of the methodology comes from "Planning the Multifucntionality of nature-based solutions in urban spaces" Alves et al. 2024. Article linked below: 
https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0264275123005632

In this project, we attempt to find optimal configurations of featured BGIs (blue-green infrastructure technology) in an urban setting through three main steps, with a fourth step planned.
     I. Risk Assessment
     II. Feasibility Assessment
     III. Optimization and Selection 
     (IV. Impact Estimation) 

Uploaded currently is the work for steps II and III. Risk assessment can be done independently. 
Please contact kim.wang@wur.nl for more information. 

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Notes on Feasibility
     Feasibility refers to whether or not a piece of land can host a certain BGI. The shapefile has certain geospatial information and is combined with the requirements of the BGI, which are given in the excel file. The feasibility assessment involves creating masks of polygons that pass each condition. 
     
Applied Conditions:
---- Landcover check
          As there are a large range of categories of "land use/land cover" through different datasets, we simplify the categories used by the Gemeente (see .... shapefile) to simple conditions that represent the most critical information needed for installing a BGI.
               Ground - representing anything that needs to be installed on soil or vegetation. On this layer, we place BGIs such as rain gardens, trees, and park space. 
               Flat Roof - representing buildings with a flat roof believed to be capable of hosting a blue/green roof. 
               Steep Roof - representing roofs that cannot host a blue/green roof. 
               Pavement - representing a special use-based category that can only host specific types of BGIs such as permeable pavement. 

---- Area check
          The minimum amount of (continuous) space needed for the BGI. 

Beta Conditions: 
     Conditions that can be checked but have not been applied in the example include: 
          Slope: the maximum slope on which the BGI can be applied. 
          Soil type: soil type needed for BGIs in the ground that have vegetation or impact infiltration.
          Groundwater level: groundwater level needed for BGIs on the ground that can potentially interact with the water table. 

Further Conditions: 
     Refinement of the conditions will lead to improved accuracy of feasibility analysis. Some possible conditions that could be integrated in the future include...
          Inserting minimum border area for BGI installation 
          Checking depth of BGI against buried utilities
          Checking distance of BGI from specific points or spaces 
          Inclusion of vertical spaces for installation 
          What else? 

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Notes on Optimization
     Current methodology estimates the performance of BGIs per objective with an indicator.  Maximization of a single objective provides a "maximum ability" of BGIs, which is a useful value for setting specific goals. This is of course a simplification and results depend highly on the indicators.
     The "ability" of each BGI is the indicator (see "bgi_catalog_v1.xlsx") multiplied by the area of application.  
     Users are to define a goal PER objective. The current optimization script tries to find a combination of BGIs that reaches the goal or is the closest possible (in terms of percentage of both goals being reached). It is also possible for users to use weighted "importance" of objectives relative to each other instead of defining specific goals. 

     Indicators given in the current excel sheet are a starting approximation for information on BGIs found primarily in the UK, the EU, and the USA. These values depend on region, climate, economy, etc. Indicators are given as performance of the BGI per each square meter of BGI installed. 
     Currently we have included two objectives: storm runoff and heat stress. For storm runoff, we use the indicator of stormwater retention volume of each BGI. For heat stress, we use the maximum cooling effect of each BGI. To add objectives, an indicator must be defined and an estimated value given for each BGI.

In Beta: optimization scripts that look to minimize cost or area needed are in progress (as well as other types of conditions). 

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

1. "bgi_catalog_v1.xlsx" 
     an excel sheet with information about BGIs that are needed for feasibility and selection scripts
-- column 1: bgi_name
     The name of the BGI 

-- column 2: install_layer
     Where the BGI needs to be installed. From an option of ground, pavement, flat roof, and steep roof. 

-- column 3: area_min
     The minimum area needed for the BGI to be viable.

-- column 4: area_max
     The maximum area recommended for the type of BGI. For some BGIs, if a larger area is available, another BGI may be preferred. For example, with a large parcel of land, installing a park is recommended over a rain garden, which tend to be for smaller areas. 

-- column 5: slope_max
     In beta: The maximum slope recommended for the type of BGI. Relevant for pavement and ground installations. 

-- column 6: soil_type
     In beta

-- column 7: CAPEX
     Estimated cost of initialization 

-- column 8: OPEX
-- column 9: water_storage_volume
-- column 10: temperature_reduction


   
    some characteristics are used to find feasibility/site selection per BGI. 
    some of these characteristics are unused at the moment but will be incorporated in future versions. 
     - infiltration crate: crates installed under roads and surfaces for the purpose of storing excess stormwater.
     - permeable pavement: types of pavement with more open pore spaces to increase infiltration rate from rainwater into the ground.
     - rain garden: a garden within a depression expressly designed for collecting rainwater.
     - blue roof: rooftop designed to temporarily contain stormwater 
     - green roof: rooftop that includes layers of soil capable of hosting a layer of vegetation 
     - tree: a tree with a border of soil, may be in a pit or box or be directly in soil. 
     - park: a green space meant to be used for recreation with a mix of plants, grass, and surface materials
     - rain storage: any container that stores rainwater. this may be a barrel, a box, and can be placed above or below ground. 
     - biohaven: modular floating islands with plants chosen to boost biodiversity, improve water quality, improve aesthetics, or other purposes

2. "example_amsterdam_neighborhood.gpkg"
--- a geopackage of a small, incomplete block of Amsterdam given as an example of what input data should contain. Data is taken from data.amsterdam.nl and maps.amsterdam.nl 
--- The shapefile is a compilation of layers from the "BGT" (Basisregistratie grootschalige topografie) and the flat roof dataset from daktype 3DBAG. 
--- this is ready to be used directly with the feasibility script given. 

3. "feasibility_script.py"
--- python code to run feasibility operations. requires both a bgi catalog in excel format and land use/land cover data in a shapefile format. once run, it creates and saves a new shapefile with results contained in it. 

for questions and comments, please contact kim.wang@wur.nl 
